<P>Xerxes in this battle is &s;aid to have lo&s;t twenty thou&s;and
men, among which were two of his brothers. But to conceal the greatne&s;s of
his lo&s;s from the army, he cau&s;ed all but a thou&s;and of tho&s;e that were
&s;lain, to be buried in holes indi&s;criminately; however, this &s;trata|gem
had very bad &s;ucce&s;s, for when the &s;oldiers of his fleet were curious
