<PB N="145" REF="148"> there was an engagement at &s;ea between the two fleets.
The Grecian fleet con&s;i&s;ted of two hundred and &s;eventy-one ve&s;&s;els.
That of the enemy had lately lo&s;t four hundred ve&s;&s;els in a &s;hipwreck,
but was &s;till greatly &s;uperior to the fleet of the Grecians. To repair this
lo&s;s by a victory, two hundred Per&s;ian ve&s;&s;els had orders to take a
compa&s;s and &s;urprize the Grecians lying in the &s;treights of Eubaea, but
the Grecians being apprized of their de&s;igns, &s;et &s;ail by night, and
&s;o, by a counter-&s;urprize, fell in with them while they were thus
&s;epa|rated from their main &s;quadron, took and &s;unk thirty, forced the
